  "doc_id": "52281",
  "text": "The patterns of MuPyV infection observed in the progeny animals born to mothers infected during pregnancy (Table 2 ) were similar to those that had been described following inoculation of newborn BALB/c mice. In general, the infection spread rapidly to multiple organs, peaking in intensity about 1 week p.i., and then was cleared from most organs in another week's time, presumably due to the maturation of the immune response [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The kidney is considered to be the major site of MuPyV persistence (Rowe et al., 1960; [CITATION_5] . The sensitive RQ-PCR assay employed in this study provides additional insights. It appears that very low copy numbers of MuPyV may remain associated with more tissues than previously suspected, with the salivary gland being the most commonly infected organ by day 21.",
